1

00:00:01,680  -->  00:00:03,920
In the previous video,

2

00:00:03,920  -->  00:00:08,140
you saw two methods for how we might choose between competing hypotheses.

3

00:00:08,140  -->  00:00:10,860
In the second method, we asked the question,

4

00:00:10,860  -->  00:00:13,280
if the null hypothesis is true,

5

00:00:13,280  -->  00:00:16,080
what is the probability of obtaining the statistic we observed in

6

00:00:16,080  -->  00:00:20,420
our data or one more extreme in favor of the alternative hypothesis?

7

00:00:20,420  -->  00:00:23,645
This probability is what is called a p-value.

8

00:00:23,645  -->  00:00:27,680
Finding the p-value involves a mix of ideas that you've learned about,

9

00:00:27,680  -->  00:00:31,340
sampling distributions, and conditional probability.

10

00:00:31,340  -->  00:00:35,225
Imagine we have a null that a population mean is equal to zero.

11

00:00:35,225  -->  00:00:36,980
Then we collect sample data,

12

00:00:36,980  -->  00:00:39,360
and we find the sample mean to be five,

13

00:00:39,360  -->  00:00:42,180
and the sample standard deviation to be two.

14

00:00:42,180  -->  00:00:47,005
Assuming the sampling distribution of your statistic follows the null hypothesis,

15

00:00:47,005  -->  00:00:49,300
what is the probability of observing

16

00:00:49,300  -->  00:00:54,060
the actual value of the statistic from your data in this distribution?

17

00:00:54,060  -->  00:00:56,120
If we want to know the probability that the

18

00:00:56,120  -->  00:00:58,620
population mean is actually greater than zero,

19

00:00:58,620  -->  00:01:00,980
you could update the hypothesis.

20

00:01:00,980  -->  00:01:03,300
Values like 6, 7,

21

00:01:03,300  -->  00:01:06,820
10 all fall out here and are even more of

22

00:01:06,820  -->  00:01:11,890
an indication that the alternative is true that our population mean is greater than zero.

23

00:01:11,890  -->  00:01:14,440
Additionally, what is the probability you

24

00:01:14,440  -->  00:01:17,840
observe something even more in favor of the alternative hypothesis?

25

00:01:17,840  -->  00:01:22,870
This shaded region here provides that probability, the p-value.

26

00:01:22,870  -->  00:01:25,780
Notice, the p-value is dependent on

27

00:01:25,780  -->  00:01:30,895
your alternative hypothesis as it determines what is considered more extreme.

28

00:01:30,895  -->  00:01:34,900
If your alternative hypothesis is that your parameter is greater than zero,

29

00:01:34,900  -->  00:01:38,045
then we shade greater than the statistic as shown here.

30

00:01:38,045  -->  00:01:42,370
However, if we change our null and alternative to look like this,

31

00:01:42,370  -->  00:01:45,090
then we shade to the left of our statistic.

32

00:01:45,090  -->  00:01:48,150
Our shading for the p-value would now look like this.

33

00:01:48,150  -->  00:01:52,090
Notice, that this would create a very large probability in this case,

34

00:01:52,090  -->  00:01:54,790
as almost the entire distribution is shaded.

35

00:01:54,790  -->  00:01:57,250
If you have a not equal sign in the alternative,

36

00:01:57,250  -->  00:01:59,770
then your shading is associated with extremes

37

00:01:59,770  -->  00:02:03,010
that are just far from the null in either direction.

38

00:02:03,010  -->  00:02:05,370
In these cases, we just care about

39

00:02:05,370  -->  00:02:09,210
statistics that are far from the null in either direction.

40

00:02:09,210  -->  00:02:11,870
We end up marking on both sides and

41

00:02:11,870  -->  00:02:15,405
shading away from the null hypothesis to find our p-value.

42

00:02:15,405  -->  00:02:18,430
This often takes people a while to wrap their heads around,

43

00:02:18,430  -->  00:02:20,770
and there are two parts to understand.

44

00:02:20,770  -->  00:02:25,410
First, you have to fully conceptualize the definition of a p-value,

45

00:02:25,410  -->  00:02:31,090
which is the conditional probability of your data given that the null hypothesis is true.

46

00:02:31,090  -->  00:02:34,070
Then, you need to figure out what to compute,

47

00:02:34,070  -->  00:02:37,250
which is visually summarized by these three images.

48

00:02:37,250  -->  00:02:40,470
You will get some practice with both of these before moving

49

00:02:40,470  -->  00:02:44,450
on and applying the ideas of a p-value to make decisions.
